RFC request for comments:
The Rule: 
RFC 793 (the TCP standard) says that if you send a packet to a closed port,
the receiver must send back a RST (Reset) packet.

The Trick: 
Nmap sends a "weird" packet (like a FIN scan). 
A standard Linux box might follow the RFC and stay silent,
while an old Windows box might send a Reset.

The Result: 
By comparing the reaction to the "Rulebook," 
Nmap can guess exactly what OS you are running.

RFC 793: TCP: 
Used for port scanning (-sS, -sT) and OS detection.

RFC 792: ICMP:
Used for "Ping" scans to see if a host is alive.

